hows that secondary cities linked rural economies and inhabitants with the outside world while insulating the traditional rural environment from the changing character of large urban centers. In this intermediate position, economic relationships and social structure changed slowly, and only in response to outside innovations such as railroads. Continuity within the secondary centers thus reinforced conservatism, accentuated the gap between the major cities and the rest of the country, and contributed to the resistance to change that characterizes much of Latin American today. The book is illustrated with photographs and maps.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- World. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBaily, Samuel L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476662340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766623/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles